 #Import legend
 library(readxl)
 ctab <- na.omit(read_excel("Globcover2009_Legend.xls", sheet = 1))
    head(ctab)
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
##   Value Label                                               Red Green  Blue
##   <dbl> <chr>                                             <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1    11 Post-flooding or irrigated croplands (or aquatic)   170   240   240
## 2    14 Rainfed croplands                                   255   255   100
## 3    20 Mosaic cropland (50-70%) / vegetation (grassland~   220   240   100
## 4    30 Mosaic vegetation (grassland/shrubland/forest) (~   205   205   102
## 5    40 Closed to open (>15%) broadleaved evergreen or s~     0   100     0
## 6    50 Closed (>40%) broadleaved deciduous forest (>5m)      0   160     0
ctable = rep(NA,max(ctab$Value)+1)
 ctable[ctab$Value+1] = 
      rgb(ctab$Red,ctab$Green,ctab$Blue,maxColorValue=255)
 r@legend@colortable = ctable
  r@legend@names = ctab$Label
   r@legend@values = ctab$Value
   r@legend@color= rgb(ctab$Red,ctab$Green,ctab$Blue,maxColorValue=255)
   r@title = "GlobCover 2009 land cover map"
# to place the legend outside the map
par(xpd = FALSE)
plot(r, axes = TRUE, main=r@title, xlab="Longitude",ylab="Latitude",cex.axis=1.3, cex.lab=1.4, cex.main=1.5,
      xlim=c(-50, 50), ylim=c(-50,50))
par(xpd = TRUE)
legend(x = -60, y = 0, legend =  r@legend@names, fill = r@legend@color, 
    cex = 0.7, inset = 0.9)

You can create a RasterStack (an object with multiple layers) from the existing RasterLayer (single band) objects.

SRTM9RGB <- stack(B1, B2, B3)
# Check the properties of the RasterStack
SRTM9RGB
## class       : RasterStack 
## dimensions  : 10500, 9600, 100800000, 3  (nrow, ncol, ncell, nlayers)

** Visualize multi-band imagery**

To combine three bands, we can use plotRGB.

plotRGB(SRTM9RGB, axes = TRUE, stretch = "lin", main = "SRTM 90 Elevation: AFRICA")

Spatial subset or crop

# Using extent
extent(SRTM9RGB)
## class       : Extent 
## xmin        : 0 
## xmax        : 9600 
## ymin        : 0 
## ymax        : 10500
##Subsetting and spatial cropping by providng coordinates for the limits of the region of interest:
#e <-  extent(0,10500,0,6000)
e <- extent(2400,7200,0,6000)

# crop SRTM9RGB by the extent
SRTM9RGB_sub <- crop(SRTM9RGB, e)
plotRGB(SRTM9RGB_sub, axes = TRUE, stretch = "lin", main = "SRTM 90 Elevation: AFRICA")

# First we define the latitudinal and longitudinal limits of Africa.
#ext.africa<-extent(-25,50,-40,40)
#Changing projection
projection(SRTM9RGB_sub) 
## [1] "+proj=merc +lon_0=0 +k=1 +x_0=0 +y_0=0 +datum=WGS84 +units=km +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0"
# transform to longitude/latitude
wgs84 <-"+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0"
wgsraster <- projectRaster(SRTM9RGB_sub, crs=CRS(wgs84))

Convert to SpatialPoints We extract the two columns with the longitude and latitude values into a matrix, and use str to view a digest:

Locations <- read.csv("Locations.csv")

loc_mat <- data.frame(long=Locations$longitude,lat=Locations$latitude)

 str(loc_mat)
## 'data.frame':    5317 obs. of  2 variables:
##  $ long: num  36.9 36.9 36.9 36.9 36.9 ...
##  $ lat : num  -0.269 -0.295 -0.303 -0.38 -0.38 ...

The SpatialPoints class extends the Spatial class by adding a coords slot, into which a matrix of point coordinates can be inserted.

getClass("SpatialPoints")
## Class "SpatialPoints" [package "sp"]
## 
## Slots:
##                                           
## Name:       coords        bbox proj4string
## Class:      matrix      matrix         CRS
## 
## Extends: "Spatial", "SpatialVector"
## 
## Known Subclasses: 
## Class "SpatialPointsDataFrame", directly
## Class "SpatialPixels", directly
## Class "SpatialPixelsDataFrame", by class "SpatialPixels", distance 2

Now create a SpatialPoints object:

#Define spatial projection
loc_sp <- SpatialPoints(loc_mat) # define projection system of SpatialPoints
 
 loc_sp
## class       : SpatialPoints 
## features    : 5317 
## extent      : 14.706, 39.318, -32.8, -0.269  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : NA
  wgs84 <-"+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0" # geographical, datum WGS84
 projection(loc_sp)<- CRS(wgs84)  # define projection system of our data
 
 summary(loc_sp)
## Object of class SpatialPoints
## Coordinates:
##          min    max
## long  14.706 39.318
## lat  -32.800 -0.269
## Is projected: FALSE 
## proj4string :
## [+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0 +ellps=WGS84]
## Number of points: 5317
